06243nam a22007215i 9780226772653DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082007ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802267726537 a10.7208/97802267726532doi  a(DE-B1597)523937  a(OCoLC)1058559277  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a591.5300aForaging :bBehavior and Ecology /ced. by David W. Stephens, Ronald C. Ydenberg, Joel S. Brown. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (576 p.) :b96 halftones, 7 line drawings, 5 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Foraging: An Overview -- tPart I. Foraging and Information Processing -- t2. Models of Information Use -- t3. Neuroethology of Foraging -- t4. Cognition for Foraging -- tPart II. Processing, Herbivory, and Storage -- t5. Food Acquisition, Processing, and Digestion -- t6. Herbivory -- t7. Energy Storage and Expenditure -- tPart III. Modern Foraging Theory -- t8. Provisioning -- t9. Foraging in the Face of Danger -- t10. Foraging with Others: Games Social Foragers Play -- tPart IV. Foraging Ecology -- t11. Foraging and Population Dynamics -- t12. Community Ecology -- t13. Foraging and the Ecology of Fear -- t14. On Foraging Theory, Humans, and the Conservation of Diversity: A Prospectus -- tContributors -- tLiterature Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aForaging is fundamental to animal survival and reproduction, yet it is much more than a simple matter of finding food; it is a biological imperative. Animals must find and consume resources to succeed, and they make extraordinary efforts to do so. For instance, pythons rarely eat, but when they do, their meals are large—as much as 60 percent larger than their own bodies. The snake’s digestive system is normally dormant, but during digestion metabolic rates can increase fortyfold. A python digesting quietly on the forest floor has the metabolic rate of thoroughbred in a dead heat. This and related foraging processes have broad applications in ecology, cognitive science, anthropology, and conservation biology—and they can be further extrapolated in economics, neurobiology, and computer science. Foraging is the first comprehensive review of the topic in more than twenty years. A monumental undertaking, this volume brings together twenty-two experts from throughout the field to offer the latest on the mechanics of foraging, modern foraging theory, and foraging ecology. The fourteen essays cover all the relevant issues, including cognition, individual behavior, caching behavior, parental behavior, antipredator behavior, social behavior, population and community ecology, herbivory, and conservation. Considering a wide range of taxa, from birds to mammals to amphibians, Foraging will be the definitive guide to the field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams-Hunt, Melissa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBednekoff, Peter A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodin, Anders, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Joel S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Joel S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Colin W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, Kristin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolt, Robert D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Lucia F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc